<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>POWER STEERING GEAR: TRW/ROSS-TAS 40, 55, 65 AND 85 - ADJUST - SECTOR SHAFT</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="adjust" graphiccount="8">
        <title>SECTOR SHAFT</title>
        <para>This adjustment can only be completed on the vehicle if the adjusting screw jam nut is accessible. This
            nut is located on the side cover.
        </para>
        <para>Photos in this section were taken on a mock frame rail for clarity.</para>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">With the engine off, rotate the steering wheel (input shaft) until the timing mark on the
                sector shaft lines up with the mark on the housing. The line on the sector shaft should be at a 90&#176;
                angle from the input shaft. The sector shaft is now on its "center of travel" (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f05003d7">Figure 137</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f05003d7" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g05003d7" filename="../figg05/G05003D7.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="192px"
                         scalefitheight="152px"/>
                <caption>Figure 137. Sector Shaft on Center of Travel</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the drag link from the pitman arm (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f05003d8">Figure 138</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f05003d8" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g05003d8" filename="../figg05/G05003D8.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="192px"
                         scalefitheight="152px"/>
                <caption>Figure 138. Remove Drag Link</caption>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <important>
                    <para>To avoid resetting the poppets, do not rotate the input shaft more than 1-1/2 turns from the
                        "center of travel" position while the drag link is disconnected.
                    </para>
                </important>
            </specpara>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">From the "center of travel" position, grasp the pitman arm and gently try to rotate it. If
                looseness or lash is felt at this point, the sector shaft is out of adjustment (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f05003d9">Figure 139</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f05003d9" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g05003d9" filename="../figg05/G05003D9.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="192px"
                         scalefitheight="152px"/>
                <caption>Figure 139. Check Sector Shaft Adjustment</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Loosen the jam nut (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f05003e0">Figure 140</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f05003e0" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g05003e0" filename="../figg05/G05003E0.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="192px"
                         scalefitheight="152px"/>
                <caption>Figure 140. Loosen Jam Nut</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">If no lash was detected in step 3, use screw to turn the shaft adjusting screw
                counterclockwise until you feel lash at the output shaft (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f05003e1">Figure 141</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f05003e1" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g05003e1" filename="../figg05/G05003E1.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="192px"
                         scalefitheight="152px"/>
                <caption>Figure 141. Turn Shaft Adjusting Screw</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Slowly turn the shaft adjusting screw clockwise until you feel no lash at the output shaft
                without using more than 10 ft-lbs. (14 N&#8226;m) of torque. From this position, turn the screw
                clockwise 1/8 to 3/16 of a turn more. Hold the adjusting screw in place and tighten the jam nut to 43
                ft-lbs. (58 N&#8226;m) (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f05003e2">Figure 142</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f05003e2" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g05003e2" filename="../figg05/G05003E2.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="192px"
                         scalefitheight="152px"/>
                <caption>Figure 142. Tighten Jam Nut</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Turn the steering wheel 1/4 turn each side of center, then back to center and recheck the
                pitman arm for lash (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f05003e3">Figure 143</hotlnk>). You should feel no lash; if there is lash, repeat steps
                4, 6 and 7.
            </para>
            <figure id="f05003e3" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g05003e3" filename="../figg05/G05003E3.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="192px"
                         scalefitheight="152px"/>
                <caption>Figure 143. Re-check Pitman Arm for Lash</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Reconnect the drag link to the pitman arm (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f05003e4">Figure 144</hotlnk>). For additional information to reconnect the drag link,
                refer to GROUP 02 - STEERING GENERAL INFORMATION AND ALIGNMENT in the CTS-5000 Master Service Manual.
            </para>
            <figure id="f05003e4" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g05003e4" filename="../figg05/G05003E4.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="192px"
                         scalefitheight="152px"/>
                <caption>Figure 144.</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
    </svcproc>
